<subSubSection id="E0039D6B67B0044B2B1E3958D319064D" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="75AD50BC4A70A16228B2A6CE0EF10470" pageNumber="2">
Diagnosis. 
<taxonomicName id="01A79134654282A0CA710C8660E0367F" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4246F4B6-CE44-4B37-85A9-AE3A2E51CBA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia tenebricosa Britz &amp; Ferraris 2003:2" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tenebricosa">Pseudolaguvia tenebricosa</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="C971217462209501E96A686F392881FC" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="2" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">P. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
(fig. 2) (morphometric data calculated from Prashad &amp; Mukerji's [1929] measurements) in having an adipose fin not reaching posterior insertion of dorsal fin (vs. adipose fin reaching dorsal fin), a narrower (23.8-25.1 vs. 26.7 % SL and 83.2-87.5 vs. 88.9 % HL) head, and a shorter snout (12.8-14.3 vs. 16.7 % SL and 44.7-50.6 vs. 55.6 % HL).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="085C9AF8038F6CB5F3882AD725905898" type="description">
<paragraph id="5631C8F632F17B3C47EF9E963714463D" pageNumber="2">Description. Small species with a maximum length of 31.5 mm SL. Morphometric information for holotype and paratypes are provided in Table 1.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3680BD148ED0489D9E89F18B720850AA" pageNumber="2">Dorsal-fin rays II, 6; pectoral-fin rays I, 8; pelvic-fin rays i,5; anal-fin rays iii,7, with the first ray very small, splint-like. Principal caudal-fin rays i,7,7,i.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="65ABBAEF5E1E9CA5AFCC9A76CDB2B5A0" pageNumber="2">Head dorsoventrally depressed, with subterminal mouth and broad fleshy lips. Upper lip continuing into maxillary barbels, the bases of which are connected to the sides of the head through a broad roughly triangular skin flap. Four pairs of barbels: Maxillary barbels extending to the base of the pectorals, lateral mandibular barbels only slightly shorter, medial mandibular barbels half as long as outer mandibular barbels, nasal barbels, arising from the internarial septum, reaching only two thirds the distance from naris to eye. Eye very small. Side and top of head scattered with numerous small keratinized tubercles; keratinized areas on dorsal surface of head may form short or longer irregular longitudinal lines that extend onto supraoccipital process; well-developed superfically situated scapular and humeral processes. Numerous tubercles along body forming parallel irregular series, one of which forms a straight line of light colored tubercles and runs along level of horizontal septum. Fleshy bases of adipose and anal fin also with tubercles. Rayed portions of fins without tubercles.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B8A0577A0D60C54891A81916884FD4A8" pageNumber="3">Pectoral fin with strong spine bearing five to seven serrae on the inner face; outer face also serrate. Dorsal spine strong with weak serrae on posterior face.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A44C692D9AD967087EBB4DA9D49A516D" pageNumber="3">Thorax and anterior portion of abdomen flattened ventrally with large adhesive organ, consisting of 14-18 longitudinal, partly merging skin folds arranged in an elongate area, 6- 7 mm long and 3-4 mm wide, with a deep median groove. Folds extend anteriorly to isthmus, so that anterior border of adhesive organ forms a V, with its tip pointing rostrally.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C1BFA60C96A3847BFCA9E4B925B8BBA3" pageNumber="3">Caudal fin deeply bifurcate with upper lobe in most specimens slightly longer than lober lobe; uppermost principal caudal ray extending as a short filament.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E4020C7C9BB7A9E196AF94409EA54989" lastPageNumber="4" pageNumber="3">Coloration. Body brown to almost black, but underside of head and belly posteriorly of insertion of pelvic fin light beige with melanophores in median groove of adhesive organ and close to anal fin insertion. Two narrow lighter bands on side of body, one extending from posterior insertion of dorsal fin in a curve down to posterior insertion of pelvic fin, another from posterior base of adipose fin to posterior insertion of anal fin. Barbels annulated black and white. Pectoral fin with dark anterior basal area, an annulated anterior face of spine, and a distal band with hyaline tip. Dorsal fin dark brown except for light posterior seam. Pelvic fin mostly hyaline, with dark basal area and narrow dark streak subdistally. Adipose fin dark brown with lighter seam. Anal fin with dark base and narrow band that forms a half circle enclosing an almost round central hyaline area; distal parts of anal fin also hyaline. Caudal fin dark brown except for two central hyaline windows in dorsal and ventral lobes.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="94A573F566F569CAA16C271D6A0D71FD" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="0C01E27EF11697D9BCDA93E2FF9B7326" pageNumber="4">Etymology. From the Latin adjective tenebricosus alluding to the dark, gloomy coloration of this species.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FA2784043093EE92097B9BEF9BBD12AB" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="B58E608468870D3F45BDAFE76EDB2487" pageNumber="5">Habitat. Pathe Chaung (fig. 3), a left bank tributary of the Sittang River, is a small hill stream, with fast running, clear water, a sandy bottom and numerous rocks and boulders. Aquatic vegetation was absent. Water temperature was 24°C, with a pH of 8.5 and a conductivity of 70 µS. All specimens were collected during the daytime. The holotype was caught with a seine among branches lying in the water, and the paratypes were collected with a battery operated electroshocker.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A46D2E05297FFAF0488F16774901A56A" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="F5CBDB6C693E9B818E2C926EC70375B3" pageNumber="5">Discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FF44B11D5674C3C2CC1B0532460B01FA" pageNumber="5">
Our new species closely resembles the erethistid 
<taxonomicName id="D47F2477CD73D9A7C15ECA7A22A06631" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">Pseudolaguvia tuberculata</taxonomicName>
and shares with that species a unique combination of two characters: (1) the presence of a distinct adhesive apparatus on the thorax possessing a median depression and consisting of longitudinal unculiferous ridges and intermittent smooth grooves and (2) well-developed scapular and cubito-humeral processes. 
<taxonomicName id="ED5FBB2092C72D99B7DACA6E0829D858" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4246F4B6-CE44-4B37-85A9-AE3A2E51CBA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia tenebricosa Britz &amp; Ferraris 2003:2" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tenebricosa">Pseudolaguvia tenebricosa</taxonomicName>
is therefore assigned to this genus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EFDE9B25B8D479CE6BF27F0B55D267C4" pageNumber="5">
Possession of longitudinal skin folds on the thorax that represent an adhesive apparatus facilitating life in fast flowing torrential waters, has been reported from representatives of the three erethistid genera 
<taxonomicName id="F2A8A4F1D55734BB4F5369E4DDF65DFA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FB9845D5-AF84-4499-B1B5-D26C5611DAE3" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Conta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Conta Hora 1950:194" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Conta</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="CD5A3410EBEBA39E5BFBB73784F6CE21" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F31BDA6F-D709-4E38-A463-312A7F1E76E1" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia Hora 1921:739" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Laguvia</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4B87E3D53273DA15EC680B5084822006" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BED2BB84-3FBC-4BDC-9032-0D537AD3F726" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia Misra 1976:253" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudolaguvia</taxonomicName>
, and the sisorid genus 
<taxonomicName id="5765F4C2148713CA4E0AB7465858A3AE" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C4304186-4FD4-4672-BDF1-AC51D2C01419" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="5" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptothorax</taxonomicName>
(Hora 1922, 1930; Wu &amp; Liu 1940; Bhatia 1950; Tilak &amp; Husain 1975; Tilak 1976; de Pinna 1996).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="712E2FD31AC7153A02DCD20B99797A8D" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="083E64939B2A8086E739F2CC4CD16338" pageNumber="6">
When trying to resolve the generic identity of the new species described in this paper, we came to accept that the species of the genera 
<taxonomicName id="8ADDDF0B57434B5DB0E189A96A5034C6" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F31BDA6F-D709-4E38-A463-312A7F1E76E1" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia Hora 1921:739" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Laguvia</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="41BF72826D70C3007C3413C1A17B16AE" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BED2BB84-3FBC-4BDC-9032-0D537AD3F726" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia Misra 1976:253" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudolaguvia</taxonomicName>
are only poorly known and the two genera are clearly in need of a revision. Hora's (1921: 739) diagnosis of the newly erected genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C36F6114209CB495C9FA78EA06EC248" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F31BDA6F-D709-4E38-A463-312A7F1E76E1" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia Hora 1921:739" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Laguvia</taxonomicName>
mentions, among other characters, that &quot;the skin covering the belly is corrugated, suggesting an adherent function.&quot; However, he (1921: 742) distinguished 
<taxonomicName id="5220500E457945DD2541969C62565ADB" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A577C234-A265-4F48-9582-041CD94D255F" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia shawi Hora 1921:740" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="shawi">L. shawi</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="C07D6D45BC53CE5CDEBE218A4A58A942" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:63C633EE-8A19-4C8D-ABE1-9431EFB552F5" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia ribeiroi Hora 1921:741" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ribeiroi">L. ribeiroi</taxonomicName>
by the absence of a thoracic adhesive apparatus in the former and its presence in the latter. Hora (1921: 742) described this apparatus in 
<taxonomicName id="A5C5C10FEE5438B49F4D7B6C0FF4C822" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:63C633EE-8A19-4C8D-ABE1-9431EFB552F5" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia ribeiroi Hora 1921:741" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ribeiroi">L. ribeiroi</taxonomicName>
as &quot;oblique grooves and ridges which form a V-shaped adhesive apparatus similar to that found in the genus 
<taxonomicName id="82E92B31615F7E80B9F39974C1D68DB7" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C4304186-4FD4-4672-BDF1-AC51D2C01419" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptothorax</taxonomicName>
but not so well-developed&quot; and Hora (1922: fig. 7a) figured well developed skin folds on the thorax of 
<taxonomicName id="A60B60950569088179F68BF764214034" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F31BDA6F-D709-4E38-A463-312A7F1E76E1" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia Hora 1921:739" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Laguvia</taxonomicName>
sp.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E3EB33DD76598126DF865DC3EF2361B7" pageNumber="6">
Subsequently, Shaw &amp; Shebbeare (1937: 105) noted that in 
<taxonomicName id="C5095ABCB8E29D291293B6CBB38EA0CF" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A577C234-A265-4F48-9582-041CD94D255F" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia shawi Hora 1921:740" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="shawi">L. shawi</taxonomicName>
, contra Hora (1921), there is &quot;a rudimentary adhesive apparatus on the thorax of fresh specimens.&quot; [These authors (104: fig. 106) also figure a specimen of 
<taxonomicName id="7B778D311746874280E0BF2669133A9A" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:63C633EE-8A19-4C8D-ABE1-9431EFB552F5" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia ribeiroi Hora 1921:741" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ribeiroi">L. ribeiroi</taxonomicName>
in lateral and ventral view with an adhesive apparatus clearly recognizable in the latter. This figure is cited as having been copied from “Rec. Ind. Mus.”, but the original description of 
<taxonomicName id="36631B8A0317DBECDC3FFF616C7E5B74" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:63C633EE-8A19-4C8D-ABE1-9431EFB552F5" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia ribeiroi Hora 1921:741" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ribeiroi">L. ribeiroi</taxonomicName>
by Hora does not contain a ventral view of the species.]
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A852584720EA62406E103B24F23E4B3A" pageNumber="6">
Menon (1955) synonymized the genus 
<taxonomicName id="D51072C6E2F6EEE174E38331326A7222" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F31BDA6F-D709-4E38-A463-312A7F1E76E1" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia Hora 1921:739" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Laguvia</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="7C569FCA57B61E02815BFBAFD32B8329" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C4304186-4FD4-4672-BDF1-AC51D2C01419" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptothorax</taxonomicName>
, because he found that the characters Hora (1921) used to distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="B623ACD5116ED174073F13CF16AF5910" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F31BDA6F-D709-4E38-A463-312A7F1E76E1" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia Hora 1921:739" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Laguvia</taxonomicName>
were also present in 
<taxonomicName id="95C45B504BB19FD897C12BC1917952F1" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C4304186-4FD4-4672-BDF1-AC51D2C01419" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptothorax</taxonomicName>
, specifically mentioning 
<taxonomicName id="E8982091B3D7A1D979F7E6036E383D68" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">P. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
(as 
<taxonomicName id="658527AF79624A7D968BA0F98407154D" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D787392-EAE4-4E95-943C-7FCCEE6F80D2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax tuberculatus Prashad &amp; Mukerji 1929:182" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculatus">G. tuberculatus</taxonomicName>
) in this context.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E21DB2278B5F378DEB9AD5E6C4273102" pageNumber="6">
Misra (1976: 247) listed 
<taxonomicName id="627C345E27B8270EFDD05A2FC4249D5C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F31BDA6F-D709-4E38-A463-312A7F1E76E1" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia Hora 1921:739" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Laguvia</taxonomicName>
as a valid genus with 3 species and noted a &quot;poorly developed adhesive apparatus composed of longitudinal plaits of skin&quot; in its generic diagnosis and in the three species descriptions, implying that such an apparatus is present in all 
<taxonomicName id="18D9CAED21757ECCFBACBFF8697EBB19" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F31BDA6F-D709-4E38-A463-312A7F1E76E1" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia Hora 1921:739" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Laguvia</taxonomicName>
species. Tilak and Hussain (1975) mention also an adhesive apparatus in 
<taxonomicName id="A9C9E5C982F8130288045312FBB469E6" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:14CB558C-59AA-44D4-9495-393CE1F93FB6" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia ribeiroi kapuri Tilak &amp; Husain 1975:1" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kapuri">L. kapuri</taxonomicName>
. Arunkumar (2000) recently described a fifth species in the genus, 
<taxonomicName id="4A3A463D712C190A60B26F3D21CD4E0A" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4A98742F-1181-43B1-B5A3-4A00F55578F3" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia manipurensis Arunkumar 2000:194" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="6" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="manipurensis">Laguvia manipurensis</taxonomicName>
, but did not mention the adhesive thoracic apparatus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8C1AACB174A3732B567F2CC19058FD8E" pageNumber="7">
Misra (1976) created the new genus 
<taxonomicName id="EEBED3518DAEC2724B3BA0576CD6220C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BED2BB84-3FBC-4BDC-9032-0D537AD3F726" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia Misra 1976:253" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudolaguvia</taxonomicName>
to accommodate 
<taxonomicName id="87EF927EB863EBA92B0A2B67ABA0DC0C" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:5D787392-EAE4-4E95-943C-7FCCEE6F80D2" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax tuberculatus Prashad &amp; Mukerji 1929:182" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculatus">Glyptothorax tuberculatus</taxonomicName>
. Misra's (1976) description of the genus contained mainly characters that are not diagnostic, but are instead widespread among erethistids and sisorids. However, he (p. 253) cited two characters in which the genus differed from other closely allied genera: &quot;1. A well developed thoracic adhesive apparatus which is considerably longer than broad with an elongated depression in the middle&quot;, and &quot;2. A contiguous adipose dorsal fin with the rayed dorsal fin.&quot; The genus 
<taxonomicName id="5ABA4C1AC59EFC5915E9999DED3DF4EC" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BED2BB84-3FBC-4BDC-9032-0D537AD3F726" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia Misra 1976:253" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudolaguvia</taxonomicName>
has remained monotypic, comprising only 
<taxonomicName id="30E7FAA2ADF29CE82E6408CFA02DAC6D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">P. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
from Sankha stream between Mogaung and Kamaing, Upper Myanmar.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C2B811EC3897CC0C27DD8396C2C2EC4" pageNumber="7">
Our 
<taxonomicNameLabel id="840A18EB68066598C3D01C072BE00048" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A576FA4E2B4BE2C6C3E0523FFA03EBB4" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:4246F4B6-CE44-4B37-85A9-AE3A2E51CBA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia tenebricosa Britz &amp; Ferraris 2003:2" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tenebricosa">Pseudolaguvia tenebricosa</taxonomicName>
, thus shares with 
<taxonomicName id="29139CE3783EA9AAE9A055F117003FF9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">P. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
a well developed adhesive apparatus with a median depression, but lacks the second character of 
<taxonomicName id="153B2CE0347B3029952CCDC8ABFE6AA3" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">P. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
, an adipose fin that is contiguous with the dorsal fin. We want to point out here that the difference between the &quot;well developed adhesive apparatus&quot; in 
<taxonomicName id="20B61227F8041E45A6BA92E4B0683BDB" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BED2BB84-3FBC-4BDC-9032-0D537AD3F726" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia Misra 1976:253" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudolaguvia</taxonomicName>
(Prashad &amp; Mukerji 1929; Misra 1976; Jayaram 1979, 1999; Talwar &amp; Jhingran 1991) and the &quot;poorly developed adhesive apparatus&quot; in some species of 
<taxonomicName id="6B1CA62EC1D587BB9DB8CD0D76E160F1" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F31BDA6F-D709-4E38-A463-312A7F1E76E1" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia Hora 1921:739" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Laguvia</taxonomicName>
(Hora 1921; Misra 1976; Jayaram 1979, 1999; Talwar &amp; Jhingran 1991) may not be a clear-cut character, as the scanning-electron-micrographs of 
<taxonomicName id="5FF375C04E7E1AC40527C140A6AFE283" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:63C633EE-8A19-4C8D-ABE1-9431EFB552F5" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia ribeiroi Hora 1921:741" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ribeiroi">L. ribeiroi</taxonomicName>
published by de Pinna (1996) show a distinct adhesive apparatus, however without the median depression typical of 
<taxonomicName id="D983AB8A75A3B0DDE2208F80A69FB335" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BED2BB84-3FBC-4BDC-9032-0D537AD3F726" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia Misra 1976:253" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudolaguvia</taxonomicName>
. In spite of the vague generic diagnosis of 
<taxonomicName id="D85680813376EEAF19995D0EBE539BFA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BED2BB84-3FBC-4BDC-9032-0D537AD3F726" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia Misra 1976:253" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudolaguvia</taxonomicName>
, the most reasonable approach to us right now is to assign the new species to this genus on the basis of its close resemblance to 
<taxonomicName id="6472CF1B4327DFFD0250A7E5730A12F7" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">P. tuberculata</taxonomicName>
and especially the shared presence of a conspicuous median depression in the well developed adhesive apparatus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6D46265D6F43BCB597F8C095E4E0C9F4" pageNumber="7">
De Pinna (1996) listed erethistid specimens from Koilla Khal, Chittagong, Bangladesh (UMMZ 209010) as 
<taxonomicName id="BD4AF9B8FD09440A048FA76D31760168" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tuberculata">Pseudolaguvia tuberculata</taxonomicName>
. However, he (personal communication, 2003) acknowledged that his identification may have been incorrect and Heok Hee Ng (personal communication, 2003), currently studying these specimens, concluded that they represent a new species whose generic assignment is not clear. Because the specimens are under study elsewhere, we cannot comment on them further, but only stress again that the group appears to be in need of a thorough revision.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5651CAC3D7B45AA674EDC9F8211DED0F" pageNumber="7">
According to de Pinna (1996), the adhesive apparatus of the erethistid genera 
<taxonomicName id="CB9669BF60B9D8F16D875DD2A367B71F" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F31BDA6F-D709-4E38-A463-312A7F1E76E1" authority="Hora, 1921" authorityName="Hora" authorityYear="1921" class="Teleostei" family="Erethistidae" genus="Laguvia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Laguvia Hora 1921:739" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Laguvia</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="6E72A9F809F9B66B146755CDE036EF09" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BED2BB84-3FBC-4BDC-9032-0D537AD3F726" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia Misra 1976:253" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudolaguvia</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="62D326F21EE3FF1925512E6EE23B70D1" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:FB9845D5-AF84-4499-B1B5-D26C5611DAE3" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Conta" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Conta Hora 1950:194" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Conta</taxonomicName>
has evolved independently from the remarkably similar apparatus of 
<taxonomicName id="F05BF770618F400585280EB81FE611FB" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:C4304186-4FD4-4672-BDF1-AC51D2C01419" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptothorax" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptothorax Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptothorax</taxonomicName>
. The latter genus was placed in the family Sisoridae by de Pinna (1996) and hypothesized to be the closest relative of a taxon consisting of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="A53C6B4D60CE57D8A97CFA5467D2A10B" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0A1502AF-3B84-4BA1-95C1-C24D72CCC5EE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudecheneis</taxonomicName>
and the subtribe Glyptosternina. The adhesive apparatus of 
<taxonomicName id="1FC23128AC28D88149511205F59D0495" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:0A1502AF-3B84-4BA1-95C1-C24D72CCC5EE" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Pseudecheneis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudecheneis Blyth 1860:154" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudecheneis</taxonomicName>
consists of transverse, not longitudinal, ridges and grooves and an adhesive apparatus is absent from members of the Glyptosternina, which is composed of the genera 
<taxonomicName id="939580E64AD166F20C1A1F70B43A86EB" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:F34DE64E-5530-4CC0-A5C5-3BD58430405D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glyptosternon" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glyptosternon McClelland 1842:584" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glyptosternon</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="5FAA28031A95C5F62BE8E942F2B19B53" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:25654FA9-3B1D-4464-8012-AEE3D499BCEB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Glaridoglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Glaridoglanis Norman 1925:574" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Glaridoglanis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="49F194C0FBB479103FCB0C9A1058A9DD" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E68EC2A2-F2FB-48AE-BBCE-ABCFD9555304" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sisoridae" genus="Oreoglanis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Oreoglanis Smith 1933:70" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="7" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Oreoglanis</taxonomicName>
, 
